list_page_teaser: As one might expect, the streets on The Wire host a wide variety of personalities, with each individual gravitating toward the types of activities best suited to their preferences.  Click to learn more!
description_html:
These images show Omar and Dennis — who was formerly known as Cutty — both have ideals and prefer reason to emotion. Bubbles and Johnny, on the other hand, prefer to be more pragmatic and emotional.

Joe's portrait shows he's outgoing, pragmatic, and can stay cool under pressure. Walon is also socialble, but is idealistic and full of warmth and passion — in some ways the opposite of Joe.

image_list.title: Omar Little
image_list.gallery_page_teaser: The Blue in Omar's spiritual portrait shows he is open to new ways of thinking, and the Green shows he is cool and rational.  Click on the image to learn more!
image_list.explain_dom: The Green in this spiritual portrait represents Omar's dominant personality trait, his fairly strong preference for being cold, rational, and objective rather than warm, emotional, and personal.  In Introverts, the dominant trait is directed inwardly, and spiritual portraits use a long horizontal line to represent this.  An example of a time when Omar is cold and impersonal comes every time he wounds someone who fails to quickly obey his demands during a robbery.
image_list.explain_aux: The Blue in this spiritual portrait represents Omar's auxiliary personality trait, his moderate preference for seeing the world more in terms of ideas than of facts.  In Introverts, the auxiliary trait is directed outwardly, and spiritual portraits use a vertical line to represent this, because it is more evident than the dominant function.  An example of a time when Omar shows this preference comes when he strategizes and plans his heists.

image_list.title: Bubbles
image_list.gallery_page_teaser: The Yellow in Bubbles' spiritual portrait shows he is open to new experiences, and the Red shows he is more emotional than logical.  Click on the image to learn more!
image_list.explain_dom: The Yellow in this spiritual portrait represents Bubbles' dominant personality trait, his need for sensual stimulation.  In Extraverts, the dominant trait is directed outwardly, and spiritual portraits use a long vertical line to represent this, because it is the side of their personality that is most evident.
image_list.explain_aux: The Red in this spiritual portrait represents Bubbles' auxiliary personality trait, his tendency to be more friendly and personable than objective and impersonal.  In Extraverts, the auxiliary trait is directed inwardly, and spiritual portraits use a horizontal line to represent this.  An example of a time when Bubbles is being more personable shows in the way he affectionately calls McNulty "McNutty."

image_list.title: Proposition Joe
image_list.gallery_page_teaser: The Yellow in Prop Joe's spiritual portrait shows he is realistic, and the Green shows he is rational.  Click on the image to learn more!
image_list.explain_dom: The Yellow in this spiritual portrait represents Prop Joe's dominant personality trait, his tendency to be realistic and pragmatic.  In Extraverts, the dominant trait is directed outwardly, and spiritual portraits use a long vertical line to represent this, because it is the side of their personality that is most evident.  An example of Prop Joe being realistic comes whenever he proposes to make a deal with someone, and finds he must adjust the terms to reach a final agreement.
image_list.explain_aux: The Green in this spiritual portrait represents Prop Joe's auxiliary personality trait, his tendency to be more logical and objective than emotional and subjective.  In Extraverts, the auxiliary trait is directed inwardly, and spiritual portraits use a horizontal line to represent this.
